  "description": {
   "en": "Seiichi Hayashi was a leading figure in the hotbed of avant-garde artistic production of 1960s and early 70s Tokyo. \nHe is best known for his lyrical and experimental manga for Garo, the famous alternative comics magazine. \nThis volume collects a selection of Hayashi’s most important manga from this period, including Red Dragonfly and Gold Pollen. \nPublished here in their original full color, these stories mix traditional Japanese aesthetics with Pop art sensibilities, \nand range in topic from the legacies of Japanese rightwing nationalism and World War II, to the pervasive influence \nof America over 1960s Japanese youth culture. \nThis first color reprinting of Hayashi’s work captures the vivid experimentation of Japanese art at this time. \nIn addition, Hayashi’s youth and beginnings as an artist are illuminated by an autobiographical essay from 1972, \ntranslated here for the first time into English. \nArt historian Ryan Holmberg discusses Hayashi’s place in postwar Japanese art and manga, \nas well as his wider contributions to the Tokyo avant-garde as a designer and experimental animator."
  },
